<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100819050819253></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100819050819253><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=78732&mid=100819050819253>Erudin</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=78732&mid=100819050819253#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=78732><span id=Scholar>Naldiin the Wise</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>33 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, Dec 12th 3:55 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.50]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Of the Erudites<br><br><br>	The so-called &amp;#8216;high men&amp;#8217;, or Erudites have a most interesting past, ceded in the history of the human cities, but broadening out into something much larger.&nbsp;&nbsp;To set the stage, at this time, Odus was held tightly by the Kerrans, while on the newly renamed Antonica, the humans had built their first two great cities.  Freeport in the east, and Qeynos in the west.  Already Freeport had become corrupted by the arts of necromancy, which had come from Neriak, only a short journey to the north.  Qeynos on the other hand, remained dedicated to law and justice, under the rule of the Bayle family.  <br><br>	Inevitably, conflict entered the land, and humans fought themselves, as well as other races without them.  The fields were stained with blood, as new explorers returned from the human frontiers with incredible news.  Elves, Dwarves, Gnomes, and magic flourished to the North (in Neriak) and to the west (in the Faydwer).  As the human cities were sent into more and bloodier turmoil with this news, a small group of intellectuals were becoming dissatisfied with the situation.  Lead by Erud, they desired to learn more about their new neighbors, and this mysterious magic power.  And so they did, one by one, they stole spells, guides, grimores and tomes from the great elven and gnomish libraries.  Finally, deciding that they had had enough of the constant strife in the great human cities, they prepared to set off for new lands.<br><br>	In secret, they gathered in Qeynos, and found passage to a small continent called Odus, where they could study in peace.  The new settlers called themselves Erudites, because Erud was their leader (as opposed to calling themselves Erudites, because Erudite is an adjective that means well learned and intelligent&amp;#8230;nice one there Verent).  Their spies continued to pilfer knowledge from Neriak, Felwithe and Ak&amp;#8217;anon as the Erudites set up their great city of stone.  There was just one problem.  The Kerrans, a sophisticated race of cat-men had already laid claim to Odus, and objected to the Erudite&amp;#8217;s demands that they leave to make way for the new (and arrogant) High Men.  But the Kerrans could do little to destroy the great new walled city of Erudin, so they were content to inhabit the southern portion of Odus, thinking the Erudites would leave them alone.<br><br>	Meanwhile, in Erudin, the Erudites were assimilating all the knowledge they could, and after some time, divided their magical castes in the same way the gnomes had done, and the elves long before both of them.  The high council banned (secretly) any study of Necromancy, not allowing those spells and tomes to be taken back to the city and studied.  But these measures were for naught&amp;#8230;Miragul, a powerful and well-respected member of Erudin society discovered these lost arts, and began studying them in secret, collecting a small following.  As his following and his knowledge grew, the Erudite High Council took note and made possibly the greatest mistake they had ever made: they declared war on all those who studied necromancy.<br><br>	The streets of Erudin went up in riots, as a great civil war began on Odus.  The newly branded Heretics fled from Erudin, and waged war in Toxulla forest.  The carnage was incredible, as the Erudites used nothing but magic to battle each other.  Miragul himself had left, and did not reappear on the scene of erudite history for many years; instead he escaped to Antonica and began to gather all the knowledge he could.<br><br>	The final battle of the Erudin Civil War was fought in the southern portion of Odus, and the Erudites succeeded in blasting the hole out of the ground, a massive pit, reaching down and touching the plane of underfoot itself.  The Kerrans who had coincidentally, inhabited this portion of Odus were transported somehow to Luclin, a hidden moon, far above the planet.  The Erudites fled back to Erudin again, afraid of the destruction they had wrought.  The heretics used the great pit and built their city of refuge, Paineel, on the sides of the hole.  It was not before long that they learned of their grave mistake, that they had touched the plane of underfoot (Brell Serilis).<br><br>	They tried their best to seal the breach, erecting a huge door between the floor of the hole and Brell&amp;#8217;s great plane.  But it was to no avail, rumor has it an over inquisitive gnome opened the door, another rumor has it that Master Yael broke it down personally.  Either way, the fact stands, the door fell.  Master Yael entered the Hole with a legion of his elemental troops on night, and slaughtered every single man, woman and child.  Only those above ground were safe, the upper city was saved.  The lower city was blocked off, to keep the monsters from rising again to finish the job.  The lower ruins of Paineel have become a staging ground of an elemental army, and a festering place of restless spirits, slaughtered in that bloody night.<br><br>	The success of Erudin and its inhabitants in uncovering the magical arts led to a backflow of knowledge across the crossing, to Qeynos, and then to Freeport, and the first human spell casters learned from the art of the Erudites.  Qeynos declared that all heretics were to be killed, but the Erudites freed their travel routes by using the long neglected sewers below the city.  Erudin and Paineel are at a silent war; too afraid of the destruction they caused to fight openly, but still hating one another deeply.  Erudin controls the only seaport, and has attempted to keep it as closed as possible.  One attempt to build a bridge across Erud&amp;#8217;s Crossing to Erudin from Qeynos to increase travel met with 3 quick assassinations of the project directors.<br>(Note, I will add information reguarding Miragul, and the Kerran's forced Exudos later)<br><br>&nbsp;<br>Naldiin Aredhel'istar<br>Magician, 52th Circle<br>&lt;Povar-Tarrew Artisiens&gt;<br>Xev Server</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
	   </form></table><ul>

</ul>
<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100819047222996></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100819047222996><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=78732&mid=100819047222996>Erudin</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=78732&mid=100819047222996#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=78732><span id=Scholar>Naldiin the Wise</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>33 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, Dec 12th 3:54 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.50]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Of the Erudites<br><br><br>	The so-called &amp;#8216;high men&amp;#8217;, or Erudites have a most interesting past, ceded in the history of the human cities, but broadening out into something much larger.&nbsp;&nbsp;To set the stage, at this time, Odus was held tightly by the Kerrans, while on the newly renamed Antonica, the humans had built their first two great cities.  Freeport in the east, and Qeynos in the west.  Already Freeport had become corrupted by the arts of necromancy, which had come from Neriak, only a short journey to the north.  Qeynos on the other hand, remained dedicated to law and justice, under the rule of the Bayle family.  <br><br>	Inevitably, conflict entered the land, and humans fought themselves, as well as other races without them.  The fields were stained with blood, as new explorers returned from the human frontiers with incredible news.  Elves, Dwarves, Gnomes, and magic flourished to the North (in Neriak) and to the west (in the Faydwer).  As the human cities were sent into more and bloodier turmoil with this news, a small group of intellectuals were becoming dissatisfied with the situation.  Lead by Erud, they desired to learn more about their new neighbors, and this mysterious magic power.  And so they did, one by one, they stole spells, guides, grimores and tomes from the great elven and gnomish libraries.  Finally, deciding that they had had enough of the constant strife in the great human cities, they prepared to set off for new lands.<br><br>	In secret, they gathered in Qeynos, and found passage to a small continent called Odus, where they could study in peace.  The new settlers called themselves Erudites, because Erud was their leader (as opposed to calling themselves Erudites, because Erudite is an adjective that means well learned and intelligent&amp;#8230;nice one there Verent).  Their spies continued to pilfer knowledge from Neriak, Felwithe and Ak&amp;#8217;anon as the Erudites set up their great city of stone.  There was just one problem.  The Kerrans, a sophisticated race of cat-men had already laid claim to Odus, and objected to the Erudite&amp;#8217;s demands that they leave to make way for the new (and arrogant) High Men.  But the Kerrans could do little to destroy the great new walled city of Erudin, so they were content to inhabit the southern portion of Odus, thinking the Erudites would leave them alone.<br><br>	Meanwhile, in Erudin, the Erudites were assimilating all the knowledge they could, and after some time, divided their magical castes in the same way the gnomes had done, and the elves long before both of them.  The high council banned (secretly) any study of Necromancy, not allowing those spells and tomes to be taken back to the city and studied.  But these measures were for naught&amp;#8230;Miragul, a powerful and well-respected member of Erudin society discovered these lost arts, and began studying them in secret, collecting a small following.  As his following and his knowledge grew, the Erudite High Council took note and made possibly the greatest mistake they had ever made: they declared war on all those who studied necromancy.<br><br>	The streets of Erudin went up in riots, as a great civil war began on Odus.  The newly branded Heretics fled from Erudin, and waged war in Toxulla forest.  The carnage was incredible, as the Erudites used nothing but magic to battle each other.  Miragul himself had left, and did not reappear on the scene of erudite history for many years; instead he escaped to Antonica and began to gather all the knowledge he could.<br><br>	The final battle of the Erudin Civil War was fought in the southern portion of Odus, and the Erudites succeeded in blasting the hole out of the ground, a massive pit, reaching down and touching the plane of underfoot itself.  The Kerrans who had coincidentally, inhabited this portion of Odus were transported somehow to Luclin, a hidden moon, far above the planet.  The Erudites fled back to Erudin again, afraid of the destruction they had wrought.  The heretics used the great pit and built their city of refuge, Paineel, on the sides of the hole.  It was not before long that they learned of their grave mistake, that they had touched the plane of underfoot (Brell Serilis).<br><br>	They tried their best to seal the breach, erecting a huge door between the floor of the hole and Brell&amp;#8217;s great plane.  But it was to no avail, rumor has it an over inquisitive gnome opened the door, another rumor has it that Master Yael broke it down personally.  Either way, the fact stands, the door fell.  Master Yael entered the Hole with a legion of his elemental troops on night, and slaughtered every single man, woman and child.  Only those above ground were safe, the upper city was saved.  The lower city was blocked off, to keep the monsters from rising again to finish the job.  The lower ruins of Paineel have become a staging ground of an elemental army, and a festering place of restless spirits, slaughtered in that bloody night.<br><br>	The success of Erudin and its inhabitants in uncovering the magical arts led to a backflow of knowledge across the crossing, to Qeynos, and then to Freeport, and the first human spell casters learned from the art of the Erudites.  Qeynos declared that all heretics were to be killed, but the Erudites freed their travel routes by using the long neglected sewers below the city.  Erudin and Paineel are at a silent war; too afraid of the destruction they caused to fight openly, but still hating one another deeply.  Erudin controls the only seaport, and has attempted to keep it as closed as possible.  One attempt to build a bridge across Erud&amp;#8217;s Crossing to Erudin from Qeynos to increase travel met with 3 quick assassinations of the project directors.<br><br>&nbsp;<br>Naldiin Aredhel'istar<br>Magician, 52th Circle<br>&lt;Povar-Tarrew Artisiens&gt;<br>Xev Server</td></tr>
