<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100378104215022></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100378104215022><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=78732&mid=100378104215022>The Ruins of Kunark, Before They Were Ruined</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=78732&mid=100378104215022#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=78732><span id=Scholar>Naldiin the Wise</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>33 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, Oct 22nd 4:04 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>A Historical Essay on Basic Kunark Lore<br><br><br>Before the Empire:&nbsp;&nbsp;The Shissir and the Green Death<br><br>	The first great empire upon Kunark was the Shissir.  A race of snake-men, they enslaved the entire continent as the dragons were organizing.  It is unknown if the trolls had been created yet, but I believe they only took form later.  The Iksar who now hold central Kunark were enslaved by the Shissir, who were more organized.  They used their Iksar slaves for labor and for food.<br><br>	The Shissir Empire rolled from Chelsith, the ruins of which now lie in the overthere, slowly rotting under the watch of scorpikie and the outpost of Venril Sathir.  The Shissir were an arrogant race, and explored the dark necromantic arts, much of which would later be unearthed by the Iksar and put to their uses.  Eventually the Iksar angered the gods, and it was decided they were to be eliminated.  Follows here, a text from &#8220;Before the Green&#8221; &#8211; from the library archives in Cabilis:<br><br>	&#8220;From it's green core the face of death begun to form. It was of no god they knew of. It opened its giant maw and spoke in tongues unknown. From the mouth of death rushed forth a green mist. The Shissar shaman began to cast spells in hopes of shielding their city and the necromancers began to assault the mist with great spells. All were futile. The mist rushed forth. The first snakes to be swallowed by the mist had their scales and flesh rot and fall from their bones. Horrid screams of suffering could be heard from within mist.&#8221;<br><br>This date sets the beginning of the Iksar calendar, at 0 B.G. (before green, referring to the mist).<br><br>	The Destruction of the Shissar was total, and left Kunark devoid of any ruling force.  Chaos followed with the froglocks, giants, dragons and the newly forged Iksar tribes fighting for resources and space.  <br><br><br><br>Tribal Rule: The Iksar Spread<br><br>	The Iksar spread out from the ruins of Chelsith outward across Kunark.  They formed into five tribes.  The Jarsath were a primitive, cannibalistic tribe whose ruined city of Varnek is located in the center of the lake of Ill Omen, sunken beneath.  An entrance to the ruins, also known as Veksar, has not been found to date.  The home of the Nathsar tribe seems to be the fortress at Chardok, but I only infer this because of items of their make seem to show there the most.  I am unaware where the Kylong or the Obulus tribes dwelt, and if anyone has information to this, please feel free to post it.  The Kunzar clan, the most important and powerful, ruled from the city of Charsis.  <br><br>	These tribes fought amongst each other, the froglocks, and perhaps the scorpikie.  I believe the scorpikie themselves were created by the Shissar, but they could have been products of Rile&#8217;s rule, and thus to come only later.<br><br><br><br>The Rise of the Kunzar, The United Iksar, and the foundation of the Sebilisan Empire<br><br>The mightiest of the Kunark Iksar clans was the Kunzar clan.  All that was needed was a strong, powerful and intelligent leader.  And this came in the form of Venril Sathir.  <br>Venril was a powerful warrior mage, dabbling in both battle and in magic, as well as an accomplished strategist.  He used his necromantic powers to summon an unrelenting army of undead to supplement his own formidable force of Iksar.  A native of Charsis he lead the Kunzar armies against the other four tribes, defeating them and placing them under his control.  AG 313, the Iksar Empire is forged under the banner of Venril Sathir.<br><br>	Sebilis, the new capitol of the united Iksar Empire, now renamed the Sebilisan Empire, is built in what is now called Trackanon&#8217;s Teeth.  Venril Sathir then enslaved the mountain giants, the froglocks and the forest giant, and enlisted them to build the great monuments across Kunark.  The slaves built great highly ornate gates and statues, to the point where now the ruins cover Kunark from north to south.  The two great military disciplines now form under Venril, the Crusaders of Greenmist (in reference to the Shissar killing fog) and the Court of Pain (weaponless warriors, now known as monks).<br><br>	Sathir grew old as his empire gained near complete dominance of Kunark.  He decided to cheat death by making a deal with Innoruuk to rise undead, unhindered by all things mortal, including death.  The great ritual was set up for the transfer of Sathir&#8217;s to immortality.  But the heir of the Sebilisan throne, Rile had different plans.  He broke the ritual, trapping Sathir&#8217;s soul in a gem, much as Miragul lost his own soul within a gem trapped within Permafrost Keep, which he hid.  He had the body cremated, and the remains can be found within Karnor&#8217;s Castle.  <br><br><br><br>The Sebilisan Empire beneath Rile and Atrebe: The war of Scale, and the End of the Empire<br><br>	Once his accomplished father was out of the way, Rile assumed command of the Sebilisan Empire.  I believe it was about this time the great City of Mist was constructed, but both Sathir&#8217;s and Atrebe&#8217;s reign could have suited the construction.  An article on the city of mist will follow shortly.  Rile was an extremely capable warrior in his own right, and was served by three great warlords, Kurn Machta, Karatukus and a vampire named Cosooth.  As a note, Kurn&#8217;s tower was named after Machta, something that should be obvious, but bears mentioning.<br><br>	Between the three great warlords and Rile&#8217;s own effort almost all of Kunark was most defiantly in the hands of the great Iksar Empire.  Several small groups of giants remained unconquered, and the Iksar had not begun their assault on the dragons of the Ring of Scale.  The threat to the dragons was obvious though, and the conflict seemed inevitable.  Thus the great dragons of Kunark called a conference.<br><br>	Thus the great dragon lords were brought together on how to deal with the Iksar.  Many of the younger dragons, lead by Trackanon, a blue poison dragon, advocated swift destruction.  But in the end patience prevailed, and it was decided to only steer events from afar, and not wage war directly.  <br><br>	Trackanon disagreed with this decision and decided, with some of his younger supporters to act decisively.  In the year 406AG, they attacked an Iksar fleet (with the captain Vlsk Irontail and Emperor Rile aboard) and destroyed it.  For the next 50 years the Ring of Scale and the Sebilisan Empire.  As Rile was already dead, his son Atrebe took control.<br><br>	Atrebe was not a warrior like his father, but instead of a necromantic bent, and went to creating new armies for the Iksar, much as the Shissar had many ages before.  To augment his ground forces, he created the Sarnak, half Iksar, half dragon.  These Sarnak have become a powerful force and have branched into a more magical and studious group named after their father, the Kly (residents of Danlir).  He also created the Sokokar, a froglock and dragon pair as flying mounts for his troops.  I have never seen one of these beasts, but if there were evidence of any still existing, I would love to be told of it.<br><br>	The battle raged and with their new beasts and weapons the Iksar began to make advances against the dragons, but the battles were bloody.  Atrebe passed away, and his son, Ganak, much more like Rile in his warrior ways, took over.  Above the Field of Bone was waged the greatest battle of the war, in which both the leader of the Ring of Scale (Jaled-Dar) and Ganak were killed in battle.  The battle itself in a draw, but not before a final raid on Sebilis in which the dragons took out the imperial palace and the final brood of the emperor, eliminating his line forever.<br><br><br><br>The Emerald Circle, and the fall of the Iksar<br><br>	Without an emperor, a new leader had to be selected.  Instead of yet another emperor and more years of dynastic rule, the Iksar selected to create the Emerald Circle.  Made up of five lords, each from the original tribal states, they attempted to increase the power of the Iksar, without having it destroyed at the hands Ring of Scale, who was now rebuilding and meddling in all affairs on Kunark.  During this time, the City of Mist prospered, and the Iksar slowly began to rebuild.<br><br>	The council dissolved into the original five tribes as they bickered.  Then even these tribes began warring on each other.  The Ring of Scale pits each leader against the next, just as they had planned to at the beginning.<br><br>	With the weakened power of the Iksar, the slaves in Sebilis saw their time to revolt.  The giants began sacking the outposts, and the blood-gill goblins invaded from Faydwer, and have by now set their bases around and in the Lake of Ill Omen.  According to one diary entry recovered from the city of mist the castle there was attacked, rumored to be by froglocks lead by a dragon (possibly Trackanon).  The City of Mist was reduced to ghosts as the Iksar fled the cities to escape the onslaught.  The Dragons finally decimated the cities, and Trackanon himself settled down in the ruins of the once great city of Sebilis.<br><br>	The Iksar Empire was no more.  The goblins, new to the continent began to build tunnels similar to their homes.  The Sarnak seized control of Chardok and a Jarsath fortress near the Lake of Ill Omen.  The undead seized the City of Mist, and the froglock and servants to Trackanon took over old Sebilis.  Kurn&#8217;s tower was inhabited by Buryani and undead.  The Iksar themselves hid for an extremely long time.  Only one great action is recorded before I find records of Cabilis having been founded.  The Crusaders of Greenmist, their remnants, made one final crusade, fighting across the Overthere, the Dreadlands and through Karnor, dislodging a tribe of Goblins.  They turned to where Cabilis is now, then occupied by more Goblins, but an evil pact gone bad destroyed the great army before it reached Cabilis.<br><br>	Kunark was ruined and war torn.  The Trolls rose and fled from the now burned out continent.  The froglock did seize the swamps, and strange creatures moved into the Emerald Jungle.<br><br>	The Lands of the Iksar were destroyed.  That is all for now.<br><br>&nbsp;<br>Naldiin Aredhel'istar<br>Magician, 52th Circle<br>&lt;Povar-Tarrew Artisiens&gt;<br>Xev Server</td></tr>
