<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=10027593634521></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f10027593634521><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=78732&mid=10027593634521>The War of the Broken Crown and the Elven Schism</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=78732&mid=10027593634521#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=78732><span id=Scholar>Naldiin the Wise</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>33 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, Oct 10th 8:16 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[4.33]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>My Historical Findings on The War of the Broken Crown<br><br>While now it is taken for granted that the elves are split distintly into three different groups, there was a time when all the elves were united a single empire.&nbsp;&nbsp;The collective elves called themselves the Dal, wiht the wood elves being considered wild elves, living on the fringes of the empire.<br><br>The Elven Empire was massive, from the Elven Capital of Caerthiel in the loping planes to the fair elven city of Takish-Hiz, is what is now the Desert of Ro.  At that time though, it was not a Desert, it was the great Elddar Forest.<br><br>On Ranthok's ridge, the nation of ogres lived, still shacken from the fall of Rallos Zek.  In the Butcher Block Mountains the Dwarves of Kaladim held a small nation as well.  Both of these peoples lived in the shadow of the Elves, whose empire was many times more powerful than thiers.<br><br>But the peace could not last forever.<br><br>Causes of the War of the Broken Crown:<br><br>Many of the Elves had grown sick of the corruption within the Empire.  They become distrustful of Innoruuk, attacking all that signified him.  They turned instead to Tunare, the goddess of growth, and the mother of the elves.  This was blasphemy to the Loyalist Elves who still followed Innoruuk.<br><br>It is unknown to this scholar if the slow destruction of the Elven city of Takish-Hiz also contributed to the war, but i would guess that it did.  AS Solusek Ro grew angry with the Elves, he detoryed thier city on the continent of Tunaria (now Antonica).  This would have created a need for the elves, to move, and the loyalist Capital of Caerthiel sat on the continent that was the next logical choice.  Add this to the growing distontent, and the tension was ripe for war.<br><br>The Rebelious elves first attacked Wielle,an Elven outpost where Freeport now stands, North of the resting place of the then dieing city of Takish-Hiz.  The loyalists within the outpost were killed.  This action brought on a war that lasted for years upon years, as both sides recruited those undecided to help them with thier fight.<br><br>The Ogres, in a rare moment of brilliance, choose this time to attack the dwarves of Kaladin.  Because the Elves could not lend aid to thier short allies, the ogres could give battle without fear of the powerful Elven armies decending upon them.  This also took the Dwarves out of the War of the Broken Crown, ensuring that thier alliance with the loyalists would mean nothing in the coming conflict.<br><br>The Deciding Battle: Aerignon<br><br>At Aerginon, the loyalist armies finally encircled the rebel armies near what is now Felwithe.  The rebels were trapped and unable to effectivly fight the coming onslaught.  The Emporer himself came from Caerthiel to the field of battle to direct his victory personally.<br><br>But what was about to become a crushing defeat for the forces of rebellion soon became a turn around victory.  The wood elves (then called wild elves) attacked the Loyalist forces from outside, pinning them between the Rebels inside the trap, and the wild elves outside it.  The emporer was killed by an assasin's dagger, and the armies of Caerthiel were forced into a route after a long and bloody battle.<br><br>After a few more years of fighting it became clear that without the Emporer the loyalists had no chance to defeat the Rebels.  The Rebel armies pushed the loyalists back to thier Capital of Caerthiel, and that night prepared to raze it to the ground.  During the night, a priest of Innoruuk led the people within Caerthiel, along with much of thier knowledge, through a great hole in the earth, and into the darkness.  Mayong Mistmoore and his servents seem to be the only Innoruuk worshiping (at that time) forces to stay on Faydwer, most likely protected by Mayong's powerful magic.<br><br>The Rebels charged the city, only to find that all the loyalists had escaped through unknown means.  The Rebels razed Caerthiel to the ground, and much of the glory of the Elven Empire went with it.  Without the aristocracy and leadership that the Empire had had before the war, it collapsed.<br><br>Aftermath<br><br>The once unified race of Elves was now split in three, with the newly named Dark Elves hating the other two.<br><br>The Rebels set up thier city of Felwithe on the spot at which the Emporer had died.  They declared themselves the High Elves or Koada'Dal.  The Wild Elves established themselves only a short distance away, in the treetop city of Kelethin, and they became known as the wood elves or Fier'Dal.  Both the High Elves and the Wood Elves took Tunare as thier main god.<br><br>For the loyalists, the patth from Caethiel was long, and the time in little or no light gave them enchanced night vision, and darknend thier skin.  When they finaly did reach the surface again, they created the fortress city of Neriak, under the earth of the Nekulatos Forest.  They spent thier time plotting to restore the empire they had lost and defeat the Elves that had forced them from thier homes.  They are called Dark Elves, or Tier'Dal, because of the color of thier skin.<br><br>IN the End, two great cities lay in rubble, Takish-Hiz had succumb to Solusek Ro, and Caerthiel had been annihalted by the High Elves.  Three new cities stood, none of which were as glorious as the great cities of the past.  The marble towers of Felwithe, the treetop platforms of Kelethin, and the underground metrapolis of Neriak.<br><br>In the end, the greatest change, was the once unified Elven Race, became a race at war with itself.<br><br>That is all.<br>&nbsp;<br>Naldiin Aredhel'istar<br>Magician, 52th Circle<br>&lt;Povar-Tarrew Artisiens&gt;<br>Xev Server</td></tr>
